```text
Layer 2 Pseudocode — Motive Bone Quaternions to JcvPCA-Ready Rotation-Vector Features

Goal:
  Convert Motive-solved global bone quaternions into filtered parent-child
  relative rotation-vector features for Layer 3 JcvPCA.

Input:
  mixed_motive_csv:
    CSV exported from Motive containing global bone rotations as quaternions.

Expected quaternion columns:
  Bone:<bone_name>:Rotation:X
  Bone:<bone_name>:Rotation:Y
  Bone:<bone_name>:Rotation:Z
  Bone:<bone_name>:Rotation:W

Output:
  relative_rotation_vectors_filtered.parquet
  relative_rotation_vectors_filtered.csv

Final feature format:
  frame
  time
  participant_id
  timepoint
  part_id
  repetition_id
  left_hip_rx
  left_hip_ry
  left_hip_rz
  left_knee_rx
  left_knee_ry
  left_knee_rz
  trunk_rx
  trunk_ry
  trunk_rz
  ...

These filtered rx/ry/rz columns are the only Layer 2 features passed to Layer 3 JcvPCA.

================================================================================
PART 0 — IMPORTANT IMPLEMENTATION ASSUMPTIONS
================================================================================

Use Motive-solved global bone quaternions as the source kinematics.

Do not use raw markers to compute final joint angles in Layer 2.
Raw markers belong to Layer 1 QC only.

Do not use global bone quaternions directly for JcvPCA.
Global bone quaternions describe bone orientation in world/lab coordinates,
not joint-relative motion.

Use parent-child relative rotations:
  q_joint(t) = inverse(q_parent_global(t)) * q_child_global(t)

Use Hamilton quaternion convention unless proven otherwise.

Assume Motive column order is:
  qx, qy, qz, qw

Document this explicitly:
  quaternion_component_order = "x,y,z,w"
  internal_quaternion_order = whichever the implementation library requires
  multiplication_convention = "Hamilton"
  relative_formula = "inverse(parent) * child"

Weak point:
  Quaternion convention is a critical failure point.
  If the library expects [w,x,y,z] but Motive exports [x,y,z,w],
  the output will be wrong even if the code runs.

================================================================================
PART 1 — LOAD AND PARSE MOTIVE CSV
================================================================================

Function load_motive_csv(file_path):

  Read CSV.

  Detect frame column:
    Possible names:
      Frame
      frame
      FrameNumber

  Detect time column:
    Possible names:
      Time
      time
      Timestamp
      Seconds

  Detect bone rotation quaternion columns.

  A bone is valid only if all four components exist:
    Rotation:X
    Rotation:Y
    Rotation:Z
    Rotation:W

  For each detected bone:
    Store:
      bone_name
      qx_column
      qy_column
      qz_column
      qw_column

  Output:
    raw_dataframe
    bone_inventory

  Export:
    bone_inventory.csv

bone_inventory.csv columns:
  bone_name
  qx_column
  qy_column
  qz_column
  qw_column
  has_qx
  has_qy
  has_qz
  has_qw
  n_frames
  n_missing_qx
  n_missing_qy
  n_missing_qz
  n_missing_qw

Hard stop if:
  no frame column found
  no time column found
  no bone quaternion columns found
  any required bone in parent_child_joint_map is missing

Weak point:
  Motive naming may differ between exports.
  Bone discovery must be robust, but it must not silently guess wrong names.

================================================================================
PART 2 — VALIDATE FRAME AND TIME BASE
================================================================================

Function validate_frame_time(raw_dataframe):

  Check:
    frame is monotonic increasing
    no duplicated frames
    no missing frame IDs, if frame IDs are integer-continuous
    time is monotonic increasing
    no duplicated timestamps
    no negative time differences

  Compute:
    dt = time[t] - time[t-1]
    median_dt
    min_dt
    max_dt
    estimated_sampling_rate = 1 / median_dt

  Expected:
    sampling_rate_hz approximately 120 Hz

  Flag:
    duplicated frames
    missing frames
    large dt gaps
    nonmonotonic time steps
    sampling rate mismatch

  Export:
    frame_time_validation_report.csv

Hard stop if:
  time is nonmonotonic
  many duplicated frames
  sampling rate cannot be estimated

Warning if:
  sampling rate differs from expected 120 Hz
  isolated dropped frames exist

Weak point:
  Filtering assumes a valid sampling rate.
  If time is wrong, Butterworth filtering and later PCA interpretation become unreliable.

================================================================================
PART 3 — LOAD OR CREATE PARENT-CHILD JOINT MAP
================================================================================

Function load_parent_child_joint_map(map_path, bone_inventory):

  Load parent_child_joint_map.csv.

Expected columns:
  joint_name
  parent_bone
  child_bone
  include_in_layer3

Example rows:
  trunk, Pelvis, Chest, true
  left_hip, Pelvis, LThigh, true
  left_knee, LThigh, LShin, true
  left_ankle, LShin, LFoot, true
  right_hip, Pelvis, RThigh, true
  right_knee, RThigh, RShin, true
  right_ankle, RShin, RFoot, true
  left_shoulder, Chest, LUArm, true
  left_elbow, LUArm, LFArm, true
  right_shoulder, Chest, RUArm, true
  right_elbow, RUArm, RFArm, true

Validate:
  every parent_bone exists in bone_inventory
  every child_bone exists in bone_inventory
  joint_name is unique
  no empty parent/child cells
  include_in_layer3 is explicitly true or false

Export copy:
  parent_child_joint_map_used.csv

Hard stop if:
  required parent or child bone is missing
  duplicate joint names exist
  map is inconsistent with detected Motive bones

Weak point:
  This map is a scientific assumption, not just code configuration.
  A wrong parent-child pair creates a wrong joint signal.

================================================================================
PART 4 — EXTRACT GLOBAL BONE QUATERNION TABLE
================================================================================

Function build_global_quaternion_table(raw_dataframe, bone_inventory):

  For each bone:
    Extract qx, qy, qz, qw as numeric arrays.

  Convert empty strings to NaN.

  Check for:
    NaN
    infinite values
    all-zero quaternions
    near-zero norm quaternions

  Output table:
    frame
    time
    <bone>_qx
    <bone>_qy
    <bone>_qz
    <bone>_qw
    ...

  Export:
    global_bone_quaternions_raw.parquet
    bone_quaternion_missingness_report.csv

Hard stop if:
  any included bone has NaN or infinite quaternion values inside analysis data
  any included bone has zero-norm quaternion frames

Warning if:
  missingness exists outside the selected analysis window

Weak point:
  Solved skeleton streams may appear complete even when marker tracking was imperfect.
  Zero missing bone quaternions does not prove marker-level tracking quality.

================================================================================
PART 5 — NORMALIZE GLOBAL QUATERNIONS
================================================================================

Function normalize_quaternions(global_quaternion_table):

  For each bone and frame:

    q = [qx, qy, qz, qw]

    norm_q = sqrt(qx^2 + qy^2 + qz^2 + qw^2)

    If norm_q is zero or very close to zero:
      flag as invalid
      stop for that file/window

    q_normalized = q / norm_q

  Record:
    mean norm before normalization
    max deviation from unit norm
    frames with large norm deviation

  Export:
    global_bone_quaternions_normalized.parquet
    quaternion_norm_report.csv

Weak point:
  Normalization fixes small numeric drift.
  It does not fix biologically wrong or solver-corrupted orientations.

================================================================================
PART 6 — GLOBAL QUATERNION SIGN-CONTINUITY CORRECTION
================================================================================

Function enforce_sign_continuity_global(normalized_global_quaternions):

  For each bone:

    For frame t from 1 to end:

      previous_q = q[t-1]
      current_q  = q[t]

      If dot(previous_q, current_q) < 0:
        q[t] = -q[t]
        record sign flip correction

  Export:
    global_bone_quaternions_sign_corrected.parquet
    quaternion_sign_flip_report_global.csv

Weak point:
  q and -q are the same rotation, but a sign flip can produce artificial jumps
  in downstream computations if not corrected.

================================================================================
PART 7 — COMPUTE PARENT-CHILD RELATIVE QUATERNIONS
================================================================================

Function compute_relative_joint_quaternions(global_sign_corrected_quaternions, parent_child_joint_map):

  For each joint in parent_child_joint_map where include_in_layer3 == true:

    parent = parent_bone
    child  = child_bone

    For each frame t:

      q_parent = global quaternion of parent at t
      q_child  = global quaternion of child at t

      q_joint = inverse(q_parent) * q_child

      Normalize q_joint again.

      Store:
        joint_qx
        joint_qy
        joint_qz
        joint_qw

  Export:
    relative_joint_quaternions_raw.parquet

Important:
  Use exact formula:
    q_joint = inverse(q_parent_global) * q_child_global

Do not use:
    q_joint = q_child * inverse(q_parent)

unless there is a documented convention requiring it.

Weak point:
  Quaternion multiplication order is one of the highest-risk implementation points.
  The code should include a small unit test with known rotations.

================================================================================
PART 8 — RELATIVE QUATERNION SIGN-CONTINUITY CORRECTION
================================================================================

Function enforce_sign_continuity_relative(relative_joint_quaternions_raw):

  For each joint:

    For frame t from 1 to end:

      previous_q = q_joint[t-1]
      current_q  = q_joint[t]

      If dot(previous_q, current_q) < 0:
        q_joint[t] = -q_joint[t]
        record sign flip correction

  Export:
    relative_joint_quaternions.parquet
    quaternion_sign_flip_report_relative.csv

Important:
  Run sign-continuity correction again after computing relative quaternions.

Reason:
  Even if global bone quaternions are sign-continuous, relative quaternions can still
  show representation-level discontinuities.

Weak point:
  Skipping this step can create artificial jumps in log-map rotation vectors.

================================================================================
PART 9 — CONVERT RELATIVE QUATERNIONS TO LOG-MAP ROTATION VECTORS
================================================================================

Function quaternion_to_rotation_vector(q_joint):

  Input:
    q_joint = [qx, qy, qz, qw]
    q_joint must be unit length.

  Step 1:
    Normalize q_joint again for numerical safety.

  Step 2:
    Optional shortest-arc convention:
      If qw < 0:
        q_joint = -q_joint

    Reason:
      Keeps angle closer to [0, pi] and reduces branch-cut jumps.

  Step 3:
    v = [qx, qy, qz]
    w = qw

  Step 4:
    Clamp w:
      w = clamp(w, -1, 1)

  Step 5:
    sin_half_angle = norm(v)

  Step 6:
    If sin_half_angle < epsilon:
      r = [0, 0, 0]

    Else:
      angle = 2 * atan2(sin_half_angle, w)
      axis = v / sin_half_angle
      r = angle * axis

  Output:
    r = [rx, ry, rz]

Function build_rotation_vector_table(relative_joint_quaternions):

  For each joint and frame:
    r = quaternion_to_rotation_vector(q_joint)

    Store:
      <joint>_rx
      <joint>_ry
      <joint>_rz

  Export:
    relative_rotation_vectors_unfiltered.parquet
    relative_rotation_vectors_unfiltered.csv

Important:
  rx, ry, rz are tangent-space rotation-vector components.
  They are not automatically anatomical flexion, abduction, or twist.

Weak point:
  Log-map can show branch-cut issues near large rotations.
  The shortest-arc convention and jump checks are essential.

================================================================================
PART 10 — ROTATION-VECTOR JUMP CHECKS BEFORE FILTERING
================================================================================

Function detect_rotation_vector_jumps(rotation_vectors_unfiltered):

  For each joint:

    For each frame t > 0:

      r_t     = [joint_rx[t], joint_ry[t], joint_rz[t]]
      r_prev  = [joint_rx[t-1], joint_ry[t-1], joint_rz[t-1]]

      jump[t] = norm(r_t - r_prev)

  For each joint compute:
    max_jump
    median_jump
    robust_threshold
    n_jump_flags
    frames_flagged

  Suggested robust threshold:
    threshold = median(jump) + K * MAD(jump)
    where K can start at 6 to 10 and should be documented.

  Export:
    rotation_vector_jump_report.csv
    rotation_vector_jump_flags.csv

Warning if:
  large isolated jumps exist
  jumps align with known marker/solver artifacts
  jumps appear near group/task analysis windows

Hard stop if:
  many severe jumps exist in the selected analysis window

Weak point:
  A clean quaternion table can still produce unstable rotation-vector trajectories.
  Do not filter blindly before inspecting major jumps.

================================================================================
PART 11 — FILTER ROTATION VECTORS IN TANGENT SPACE
================================================================================

Function filter_rotation_vectors(rotation_vectors_unfiltered, sampling_rate_hz, cutoff_hz=10):

  Input:
    continuous full-session or full-Part-1 rotation-vector table.

  Important:
    Prefer filtering the continuous session or full Part 1 before cutting short
    group/task windows.

  Reason:
    Filtering short segments independently can create edge artifacts.

  Filter:
    Butterworth low-pass
    cutoff_hz = 10
    sampling_rate_hz = estimated from time column, expected about 120 Hz
    zero_phase = true for offline analysis
    filter_order = documented, e.g. 4

  For each feature column:
    Apply filter independently:
      joint_rx
      joint_ry
      joint_rz

  Do not filter:
    frame
    time
    metadata columns

  Export:
    relative_rotation_vectors_filtered.parquet
    relative_rotation_vectors_filtered.csv

Metadata:
  filter_type = "Butterworth low-pass"
  cutoff_hz = 10
  sampling_rate_hz
  filter_order
  zero_phase_true_false
  filtered_before_segmentation = true/false
  software_versions

Weak point:
  Filtering is a major source of downstream PCA differences.
  Keep filter settings fixed and documented.

================================================================================
PART 12 — OPTIONAL FILTER SENSITIVITY OUTPUTS
================================================================================

Function run_filter_sensitivity(rotation_vectors_unfiltered):

  For cutoff_hz in [6, 10, 15]:

    filtered_table = filter_rotation_vectors(
      rotation_vectors_unfiltered,
      sampling_rate_hz,
      cutoff_hz
    )

    Export:
      relative_rotation_vectors_filtered_6Hz.parquet
      relative_rotation_vectors_filtered_10Hz.parquet
      relative_rotation_vectors_filtered_15Hz.parquet

  Create:
    filter_sensitivity_summary.csv

Summary fields:
  cutoff_hz
  n_features
  mean_absolute_difference_vs_10Hz
  max_absolute_difference_vs_10Hz
  notes

Layer 3 can later rerun JcvPCA on these versions.

Weak point:
  If Layer 3 JcvPCA direction changes strongly across 6/10/15 Hz,
  the result should be marked unstable.

================================================================================
PART 13 — ATTACH SESSION/TASK METADATA FOR LAYER 3
================================================================================

Function attach_metadata(filtered_rotation_vectors, session_metadata):

  Add columns:
    participant_id
    timepoint        # T1, T2, T3
    part_id          # P1
    repetition_id    # r1, r2
    source_file
    sampling_rate_hz
    filter_cutoff_hz

  Do not segment permanently here unless needed.

  Preferred:
    Layer 2 outputs continuous filtered features.
    Layer 3 performs group/task extraction using manually verified boundaries.

  Optional:
    Also export segment-ready copies if boundaries are already verified.

Output:
  layer2_feature_table_continuous.parquet

Weak point:
  Segment boundaries should be manually/video verified.
  Do not rely only on transcript timestamps for final analysis.

================================================================================
PART 14 — CREATE FEATURE MANIFEST FOR LAYER 3
================================================================================

Function create_layer3_feature_manifest(filtered_rotation_vectors):

  For each rx/ry/rz feature column:

    Parse:
      joint_name
      component  # rx, ry, rz

    Store:
      feature_index
      feature_name
      joint_name
      component
      include_in_layer3 = true

  Export:
    layer3_feature_manifest.csv

Example:
  0, trunk_rx, trunk, rx, true
  1, trunk_ry, trunk, ry, true
  2, trunk_rz, trunk, rz, true
  3, left_hip_rx, left_hip, rx, true
  ...

Important:
  This manifest defines exact feature order for JcvPCA.

Weak point:
  JcvPCA requires identical feature order between A and B.
  The manifest should be reused by Layer 3, not regenerated differently per file.

================================================================================
PART 15 — FINAL OUTPUT VALIDATION
================================================================================

Function validate_layer2_final_outputs(filtered_rotation_vectors, feature_manifest):

  Check:
    frame/time present
    metadata columns present
    all manifest features exist
    no NaN in feature columns
    no infinite values
    all features numeric
    feature order matches manifest
    at least one rx/ry/rz triplet per included joint
    sampling rate metadata present
    filter metadata present

  For each joint:
    confirm exactly:
      joint_rx
      joint_ry
      joint_rz

  Export:
    layer2_final_validation_report.csv

Hard stop if:
  missing features
  NaN/infinite values in final features
  inconsistent feature order
  missing metadata needed for Layer 3

================================================================================
PART 16 — REQUIRED OUTPUT FILES
================================================================================

Primary Layer 2 outputs:
  relative_rotation_vectors_filtered.parquet
  relative_rotation_vectors_filtered.csv
  layer2_feature_table_continuous.parquet
  layer3_feature_manifest.csv

Supporting outputs:
  bone_inventory.csv
  parent_child_joint_map_used.csv
  frame_time_validation_report.csv
  bone_quaternion_missingness_report.csv
  quaternion_norm_report.csv
  quaternion_sign_flip_report_global.csv
  quaternion_sign_flip_report_relative.csv
  relative_joint_quaternions.parquet
  relative_rotation_vectors_unfiltered.parquet
  rotation_vector_jump_report.csv
  rotation_vector_jump_flags.csv
  filter_sensitivity_summary.csv
  layer2_final_validation_report.csv
  layer2_metadata.json

layer2_metadata.json should include:
  source_file
  participant_id
  timepoint
  part_id
  repetition_id
  quaternion_component_order
  internal_quaternion_order
  multiplication_convention
  relative_rotation_formula
  parent_child_joint_map_file
  sampling_rate_hz
  filter_type
  filter_order
  filter_cutoff_hz
  zero_phase_filtering
  filtered_before_segmentation
  log_map_shortest_arc_true_false
  final_feature_representation = "parent-child relative rotation vectors"
  output_for_layer3 = "filtered joint_rx/joint_ry/joint_rz features"

================================================================================
PART 17 — IMPLEMENTATION WEAK POINTS TO HANDLE CAREFULLY
================================================================================

1. Motive quaternion column parsing:
   Do not silently misread X/Y/Z/W order.

2. Quaternion library convention:
   Many libraries use [w,x,y,z], while Motive often exports X/Y/Z/W.
   Convert explicitly and test.

3. Quaternion multiplication order:
   Use:
     inverse(parent) * child
   Document and unit-test it.

4. Sign-continuity:
   Apply once to global bone quaternions and again to relative joint quaternions.

5. Log-map edge cases:
   Handle near-zero rotations, clamp qw, and consider shortest-arc convention.

6. Filtering:
   Filter continuous signals before group/task segmentation when possible.
   Avoid filtering very short task windows independently.

7. Segment boundaries:
   Layer 2 should produce continuous filtered features.
   Layer 3 should use manually/video-verified group/task windows.

8. Anatomical interpretation:
   rx/ry/rz are not anatomical flexion/abduction/twist angles.
   They are rotation-vector components.
   Layer 3 should group rx/ry/rz per joint for joint-level JcvPCA.

9. Dependency on Motive:
   These are Motive-derived skeleton kinematic features.
   They are not independently reconstructed anatomical joint angles.

10. Layer 3 compatibility:
   The final feature manifest must be stable across T1, T2, T3, r1, and r2.
```
